"{\"uid\": \"express.co.uk-sport-othersport-1931960-olympics-denied-medal-penis-pole-vault\", \"text\": \"  A French pole vaulter who missed out on the final at theParis Olympicsbecause of his penis has been urged to 'call a drag queen' by a former tennis star.  Anthony Ammirati sent the internet into a frenzy over the weekend when his manhood clipped the 5.70-metre bar, denying him a spot in Monday's final.  It was a bizarre moment, and now ex-professional tennis player and Serena Williams' former coach Rennae Stubbs has since weighed in on the incident.  Taking to social media to offer a tip to Ammirati,Stubbs commented: \\\"Seriously!!! When your sport is all about getting your body over a bar and it's a matter of millimetres!  \\\"My man! Call a drag queen! She will teach u how to tuck it! This is unbelievable!\\\"  Stubbs was referencing a practice called 'tucking' adopted by drag queens, which sees the male genitals tucked between the legs and the buttocks - something which would have certainly helped Ammirati out in his event.  Among the memes and the online jibes, Ammirati has been dealing with the disappointment of his Olympic dream coming to an end early.  In the aftermath of the weekend mishap, Ammirati broke his silence on his exit from the competition, but the Frenchman did not directly reference his penis-related gaffe.  Pick up your ultimate guide to the Olympics! Going for Gold provides the day-by-day rundown of what's on and when. Click here to buy.      Speaking to the French Athletics Federation, Ammirati said: \\\"It's a big disappointment. I am a bit gutted, because I did not miss anything on the third attempt at 5.70 m.  \\\"What I did miss was a bit of jumping in training to fine-tune the settings. Just a technical session.  He added: \\\"I was 100 per cent physically, but I was missing a bit of pole vault.  \\\"The conditions were good. It's the first time I have started a competition without any stress.  Do not miss:Carlos Alcaraz cries and stops interview after losing Olympic gold to Djokovic  Do not miss:Team GB's Amber Rutter 'cheated out of Olympic gold' after controversial final  Do not miss:BBC viewers fume 'we are fed up' as Olympics coverage becomes 'insufferable'  \\\"As I was a total outsider, I only had one goal: to interact with the audience. I was almost there.\\\"  Thankfully for Ammirati, he wasn't the only pole vaulter to go viral over the weekend, with Estonian athlete Karel Tilga also enduring an afternoon to forget.  We use your sign-up to provide content in ways you have consented to and to improve our understanding of you. This may include adverts from us and 3rd parties based on our understanding. You can unsubscribe at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy  Unlike Ammirati, the 26-year-old did not come close to clearing the bar, instead, his pole got stuck in the floor with Tilga left dangling precariously in the air.  Tilga eventually came back down to earth, but it wasn't without a bang, as the Estonian crashed to the floor in a less-than-graceful heap.  SEARCH  CONNECT WITH US  TODAY'S PAPER  See today's front and back pages, download the newspaper, order back issues and use the historic Daily Express newspaper archive.  EXPRESS.CO.UK  Daily Express uses notifications to keep you updated\"}"